Bedrock and PFOA Concentration Analysis:
In order to understand the influence of bedrock types on PFOA groundwater migration, a geospatial and statistical analysis was conducted. Using GIS, a polygon and point intersection was executed to assign corresponding bedrock categories to the attribute table of each well location. This spatial join intersected the average PFOA concentration for each well with the regional bedrock geology layer generated by Jon Kim (2017) of the Vermont Geological Survey. All sampling points that did not fall directly within the delineated bedrock polygons were excluded from the analysis. A map illustrating the well average PFOA concentrations relative to the underlying bedrock distribution is shown in Figure [5]. 
We ran a one-way ANOVA and Tukey HSD pairwise statistical tests of the results to see if there was a statistically significant difference in contamination levels within the different formations. The results showed that there is strong evidence (p<0.001) that there is a difference in means between different bedrock pairs, with pairs including the Shelburne (os) formation having a higher difference in means [Figure 6].  
Results of the analysis show that there is a statistically significant difference, with the Walloomsac formation having lower concentrations and the Shelburne, Dunham, Cheshire, and Monkton formations having higher concentrations. The Walloomsac formation is located dominantly upwind of ChemFab; it is expected to have lower concentrations. Similarly, the Shelburne has very high concentrations, as it lies directly beneath the factory. However, inconsistent contamination levels across the other downwind formations are unexpected; further study is appropriate.
